> We're big fans of baking, rather than frying, our meatballs for a healthier
> alternative to this dinnertime staple. But don't worry, the dish is still
> jam-packed with flavor thanks to a sweet hoisin glaze, roasted sweet potatoes,
> and crispy veggies. One bite and you'll be hooked.

Wash and dry all produce. Preheat the oven to 450 degrees. Halve the
@sweet potatoes{24%ounce} lengthwise, then thinly slice into ¼-inch half moons.
Peel and mince the @ginger{1%thumb}. Thinly slice the @scallions{4}, then chop
until finely minced.

== Roasting the Sweet Potatoes ==

Toss the sweet potatoes on a #baking sheet{} with 1 Tablespoon
@olive oil{1%tablespoon} and a pinch of @salt{pinch} and @pepper{}. Place in the
oven for about ~{20%minutes}, flipping once, until golden brown.

== Making the Meatballs ==

In a #medium bowl{}, combine the ginger, scallions, @ground beef{20%ounce},
@panko breadcrumbs{1/2%cup}, and @sugar{2%teaspoon}. Season with
@salt{1 1/2%teaspoon} and @pepper{}. Form into 1-inch meatballs, and place onto
one side of a lightly oiled baking sheet.

== Roasting with Broccolini ==

Place the @baby broccoli{12%ounce} on the opposite side of the baking sheet with
the meatballs. Toss with a large drizzle of oil and a pinch of salt and pepper.
Place in the oven for ~{15%minutes}, until tender and slightly crispy.

== Glazing and Serving ==

After 15 minutes, glaze each meatball with a little @hoisin sauce jar{2}.
Remove the broccolini from the baking sheet, then return to the oven for
about ~{5%minutes}.

Cut the @lime{1} into wedges. Serve the meatballs with the broccolini and sweet
potatoes on the side. Squeeze over a lime wedge and enjoy!